posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114936153
Calling it a drone note implies it lasts as long as the entire melody.
Calling it a pedal tone implies it's in the bass and has some functional harmonic significance, usually a held dominant or tonic.
But the basic concept is the same and there are plenty of long held notes that don't apply to either of those situations. I don't think there's any big issue even if you mix up the two terms.

I've often contemplated to myself wether or not someone could sue over an AI using their likeness.
I'm no lawyer, but I THINK your likeness is considered a copyrighted asset, it's just that 99% of the time when someone else is using your likeness, it's in the name of parody, so it's almost always fair use. One could argue that using an AI likeness of someone else is an intentional attempt at deceiving or tricking the general public, much like bootleg merchandise, thus under current copyright framework, it's not considered fair use. And it also showcases the core limitation of AI, it cannot exist in a vacuum, it relies on existing/outside inputs. In fact, over-training is a real issue in AI development, where AI art generators get too good at recreating existing datasets to the point where the output is no longer creative or transformative.

The final evaluation is that Rogers is the core genius but he does his best work with Gilmour contributing. It's impossible for non-industry people to understand the financial terrorism that happens at the highest tiers of the music business. At various points I'm 100% sure that Waters and Gilmour have blackmailed each other, strong-armed each other, extorted each other, and intellectually raped each other. That's just par for the course when you have high-powered executives, your own agents, and the tax-man breathing down your neck 24/7. It's sad that these great artists are forced to reckon with the demands of becoming rich, particularly when they're usually ill-suited to managing their finances, mostly coming from working or middle-class backgrounds. Still, the musical journey of Pink Floyd was obviously steered by Roger Waters. Gilmour ultimately capitalized via what the military calls "stolen valour." But both proved conclusively with their solo and Waters-less Pink Floyd efforts that they were much more relevant together than apart.

Music Shows are a big part of how the public and international fans get exposed (kek) to new music, so it really kneecapped the growth. It's coming back now but it's taken like a decade.

This is the producer behind what was arguably the most successful kpop song of 2022 and one of the most successful songs of 2023 so far (Hype Boy and Ditto by NewJeans, respectively, both really good).
After working as a producer for big kpop groups for years he released his first solo album in 2022 (a few months before working with NewJeans).
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZHbnVPDsYX8
It's essentially a concept album that serves as an homage to ppongjjak (an energetic, over-the-top, extremely tacky subgenre of Korean techno/synth-pop music) and other similar subgenres. It's a fun listen.

>>114932156
if by "fingerstyle" you mean fingerpicking on steel string acoustic rather than playing classical guitar on nylon string, i'd recommend getting a book. if you play piano, you already know how to read sheet music, so you've got a leg up on a lot of guitarists in that respect already.
i haven't tried this specific book, but i've used another of the Mel Bay books to learn bass guitar and it worked great for me. Look into Mel Bay Complete Fingerstyle Guitar Method.
a lot of people would suggest getting a music teacher, and that may help you to have someone encouraging good practice habits and discouraging bad ones, but i've found that a lot of guitar teachers aren't actually very good about developing your skills in the long run, but can be really helpful getting you started.
tl;dr: buy a fingerstyle book, find a music store in your area that has guitar teachers and try out some lessons.

>self-oscillation in audio is a process where the level of a lowpass filter is brought all the way down and the resonance is brought all the way up in order to produce a pure sine wave
This is one of the most bizarre things I've ever heard of in my life.

1. It's highly convoluted
2. I have no idea what the utility is supposed to be when it's producing the most basic thing in all of audio. The answer is that apparently some synthesizers apparently don't come equipped with a pure sine wave
3. The term "self-oscillation" appears to make no sense at all
4. The Wikipedia entry for "self-oscillation" when not regarding audio actually does make sense, and doesn't resemble the audio terminology at all

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-oscillation

So... is literally everybody just misusing this term?
I don't know what else to say.
By all accounts it appears that an audio engineer heard this term from somewhere else, used it here and it just... stuck

Or am I missing something

posts.name: Anonymous

>>114930406
Thats not a very good way to pan instruments and most beatles fans prefer the mono mixes to the stereo mixes.

The norm is.

Drums center
vocals center (overdubs and backup vocals panned a bit to right/left)
Guitars Left/right (if you have two guitarists, you pan them left/right. If a single guitar you either double track and pan left/right or you record with two microphones to capture enough stereo width)
Bass center

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114930406
Alright, I'll help you. Bass-heavy instruments like bass guitar and kick drum feel best in the centre - They ground the song. The back-beat(snare) also feels good in the center. Lead instruments or lead vocals feel good in the center - they are the center after all.

Everything else you can pan to create space in the mix, and give room for the other elements. Keep your stereo image balanced - If you have a guitar on the right, you want something else on the left to balance it out, like another guitar or keys.

George Harrison was born in Liverpool, England, on February 25th, 1943. From a young age, he was drawn to music and began playing the guitar at the age of 14. In 1956, he met Paul McCartney and John Lennon, who were forming a band, and soon joined as the lead guitarist. The band was called the Beatles, and it would go on to become one of the most influential and successful musical groups in history.

Harrison's musical style was heavily influenced by Indian classical music, and he introduced the sitar, an Indian stringed instrument, to Western music through the Beatles' song "Norwegian Wood." He also wrote several of the band's most popular songs, including "Something," "Here Comes the Sun," and "While My Guitar Gently Weeps."

Despite the Beatles' immense success, Harrison became increasingly dissatisfied with the group in the late 1960s. The band's manager, Brian Epstein, had died, and they were facing new challenges as they tried to move away from their "mop-top" image and experiment with more avant-garde styles of music. Harrison also felt that his contributions to the band were not being given the recognition they deserved.

By the time the Beatles began recording their album "Let it Be," Harrison was considering leaving the band. He was frustrated with the creative direction of the album and felt that his ideas were being ignored. He also felt that he was not being given enough opportunities to showcase his own music.

Finally, in January 1969, Harrison quit the Beatles during the recording sessions for "Let it Be." This decision was not taken lightly, and he later wrote in his autobiography that it was one of the most difficult things he had ever done. He felt that he needed to pursue his own musical vision and was no longer able to do so within the context of the band. -
